Constant TOKEN_RANGE_INCL as Integer is 8174
Constant TOKEN_RANGE_EXCL as Integer is 8175

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Ruby source is byte-addressable UTF-8; identifiers and keywords are ASCII so
a byte cursor is sufficient. The lexer state is a 40-byte record (5 x i64):
source handle (0), byte position (8, 0-based), current line (16, 1-based),
current column (24, 1-based), and the cached source length (32). Caching the
length avoids re-walking the buffer on every scan-loop bound test.
@End Reasoning

Type called "RubyLexer":
    source as Integer
    position as Integer
    line as Integer
    column as Integer
    length as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Arena allocation matches the parser's lifetime: the lexer and every token it
produces live exactly as long as the parse driver call, then are released as
one arena batch. Initialising line/column to 1 and length once lets the
scanners run without first-character special cases.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_ruby_lexer" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create Ruby lexer from a source string handle

    Let lexer be proc allocate from Arena with 40
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with lexer, 0, source
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with lexer, 16, 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with lexer, 24, 1
    Let len be proc string_length from StringCore with source
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with lexer, 32, len

    Return lexer
End Process

@Reasoning:
A token is a 32-byte record holding the type tag (0), lexeme handle (8),
source line (16), and column (24). Centralising construction keeps the token
shape defined in exactly one place.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_token" takes token_type as Integer, lexeme as Integer, line as Integer, column as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create a token record with type and source metadata

    Let token be proc allocate from Arena with 32
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with token, 0, token_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with token, 8, lexeme
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with token, 16, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with token, 24, column

    Return token
End Process

@Reasoning:
Copies the half-open byte range [start_pos, end_pos) of the source buffer
into a freshly arena-allocated NUL-terminated string so each token owns a
stable lexeme handle independent of cursor movement. A reversed range yields
the empty string rather than corrupting memory.
@End Reasoning
Process called "ruby_substring" takes source as Integer, start_pos as Integer, end_pos as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Copy source bytes [start_pos, end_pos) into a new NUL-terminated string

    Let len be end_pos minus start_pos
    If len is less than 0:
        Set len to 0
    End If

    Let buffer be proc allocate from Arena with len plus 1
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than len:
        Let ch be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with source, start_pos plus i
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, i, ch
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, len, 0
    Return buffer
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Character Classification
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Digit classifier for numeric-literal scanning and identifier tails. Tests the
ASCII range 48..57 ('0'..'9').
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_digit" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if a byte is an ASCII decimal digit

    If ch is greater than or equal to 48:
        If ch is less than or equal to 57:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Identifier-start classifier: Ruby identifiers begin with a letter or
underscore. Uppercase-led names are constants, but that distinction is made
by the caller after the full name is read; here we only test letter-ness.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_alpha" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if a byte is an ASCII letter or underscore

    If ch is equal to 95:
        Return 1
    End If

    If ch is greater than or equal to 65:
        If ch is less than or equal to 90:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    If ch is greater than or equal to 97:
        If ch is less than or equal to 122:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Identifier-tail classifier: letters, digits, and underscore.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_alnum" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if a byte is alphanumeric or underscore

    Let digit_check be proc is_digit with ch
    If digit_check is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let alpha_check be proc is_alpha with ch
    Return alpha_check
End Process

@Reasoning:
Uppercase classifier distinguishes Ruby constants (Foo, MAX) from local
variables/methods. Tests the ASCII range 65..90 ('A'..'Z').
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_upper" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if a byte is an ASCII uppercase letter

    If ch is greater than or equal to 65:
        If ch is less than or equal to 90:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Hexadecimal classifier supports 0x... integer literals: 0..9, A..F, a..f.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_hex_digit" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if a byte is a hexadecimal digit

    Let digit_check be proc is_digit with ch
    If digit_check is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    If ch is greater than or equal to 65:
        If ch is less than or equal to 70:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    If ch is greater than or equal to 97:
        If ch is less than or equal to 102:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Horizontal-whitespace classifier. Newline is NOT treated as whitespace by
this predicate because Ruby newlines are statement terminators that the
scanner must surface as TOKEN_NEWLINE; only space (0x20), tab (0x09), and
carriage return (0x0D) are skippable inter-token whitespace.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_hspace" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if a byte is horizontal whitespace (space, tab, CR)

    If ch is equal to 32:
        Return 1
    End If

    If ch is equal to 9:
        Return 1
    End If

    If ch is equal to 13:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Cursor Utilities
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Read-only cursor accessor returning 0 (EOF sentinel) at or past the source
length, matching how scanners detect end-of-input without a separate flag.
@End Reasoning
Process called "current_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Read the byte at the cursor without advancing

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 0
    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
    Let length be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 32

    If position is greater than or equal to length:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, position
    Return ch
End Process

@Reasoning:
Multi-byte lookahead for disambiguating multi-character operators ("**=",
"<=>", "&.", "..." etc.) without committing the cursor. Returns 0 past EOF.
@End Reasoning
Process called "peek_char" takes lexer as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Read the byte offset positions ahead of the cursor

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 0
    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
    Let length be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 32
    Let peek_pos be position plus offset

    If peek_pos is greater than or equal to length:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, peek_pos
    Return ch
End Process

@Reasoning:
Cursor-advancing read that maintains line/column for diagnostics. A newline
(0x0A) bumps line and resets column to 1; any other byte bumps column.
Returns the byte that was at the original cursor.
@End Reasoning
Process called "advance_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Consume the current byte and update line/column counters

    Let ch be proc current_char with lexer
    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 24

    Set position to position plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8, position

    If ch is equal to 10:
        Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 16
        Set line to line plus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with lexer, 16, line
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with lexer, 24, 1
    Otherwise:
        Set column to column plus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with lexer, 24, column
    End If

    Return ch
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Whitespace and Comment Skipping
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Skips horizontal whitespace only. Backslash-newline line continuation is
also consumed here: a backslash immediately followed by a newline joins the
two physical lines into one logical line, so both bytes are skipped and the
scan continues past the newline without emitting TOKEN_NEWLINE.
@End Reasoning
Process called "skip_hspace" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip spaces, tabs, CR, and backslash-newline continuations

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let ch be proc current_char with lexer
        Let is_ws be proc is_hspace with ch

        If is_ws is equal to 1:
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise:
            If ch is equal to 92:
                Let nxt be proc peek_char with lexer, 1
                If nxt is equal to 10:
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                Otherwise:
                    Return 1
                End If
            Otherwise:
                Return 1
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Skips a Ruby '#' line comment up to (but not including) the terminating
newline, so the main loop still surfaces that newline as TOKEN_NEWLINE and a
comment never silently merges two statements.
@End Reasoning
Process called "skip_line_comment" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip a # comment to end of line, leaving the newline unconsumed

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let ch be proc current_char with lexer
        If ch is equal to 0:
            Return 1
        End If
        If ch is equal to 10:
            Return 1
        End If
        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Detects whether the cursor sits at the start of a line on an "=begin"
directive, which opens a Ruby block comment that runs until a line starting
with "=end". The =begin/=end markers must be at column 1 in Ruby; this
predicate is only consulted by next_token when the previous token was a
newline (or at start of file), so the column-1 rule is satisfied by
construction. Returns 1 when the next five bytes spell "=begin".
@End Reasoning
Process called "at_block_comment_open" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check whether the cursor begins an =begin block-comment opener

    Let c0 be proc current_char with lexer
    If c0 is not equal to 61:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let c1 be proc peek_char with lexer, 1
    If c1 is not equal to 98:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let c2 be proc peek_char with lexer, 2
    If c2 is not equal to 101:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let c3 be proc peek_char with lexer, 3
    If c3 is not equal to 103:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let c4 be proc peek_char with lexer, 4
    If c4 is not equal to 105:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let c5 be proc peek_char with lexer, 5
    If c5 is not equal to 110:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Consumes an =begin ... =end block comment. The scan advances line by line;
each time the cursor sits at the start of a line it tests for "=end" and, on
match, drains that line and returns. EOF without a closing =end exits
silently so malformed input cannot hang the lexer.
@End Reasoning
Process called "skip_block_comment" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip an =begin ... =end multi-line comment

    Note: Consume the =begin line entirely
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let ch be proc current_char with lexer
        If ch is equal to 0:
            Return 1
        End If
        If ch is equal to 10:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Break
        End If
        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While

    Note: Drain lines until one begins with =end
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let c be proc current_char with lexer
        If c is equal to 0:
            Return 1
        End If

        Note: Test for "=end" at the start of this line
        If c is equal to 61:
            Let e1 be proc peek_char with lexer, 1
            Let e2 be proc peek_char with lexer, 2
            Let e3 be proc peek_char with lexer, 3
            If e1 is equal to 101:
                If e2 is equal to 110:
                    If e3 is equal to 100:
                        Note: Drain the rest of the =end line
                        While 1 is equal to 1:
                            Let d be proc current_char with lexer
                            If d is equal to 0:
                                Return 1
                            End If
                            If d is equal to 10:
                                proc advance_char with lexer
                                Return 1
                            End If
                            proc advance_char with lexer
                        End While
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Note: Not the closing line - drain it and continue
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Let g be proc current_char with lexer
            If g is equal to 0:
                Return 1
            End If
            If g is equal to 10:
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Break
            End If
            proc advance_char with lexer
        End While
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Number Lexing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Scans a Ruby numeric literal. Detects the kind by peeking the prefix:
  - 0x / 0X : hexadecimal integer
  - 0b / 0B : binary integer
  - 0o / 0O : octal integer
otherwise a decimal scan that may grow a fractional part (digit-after-dot is
required so "1..5" tokenises as a range, not "1." followed by ".5") and an
optional exponent. Underscores between digits are allowed and consumed.
The resulting token is TOKEN_FLOAT when a '.' or exponent was seen, else
TOKEN_INTEGER.
@End Reasoning
Process called "lex_number" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex an integer or float literal

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 0
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 16
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 24

    Let ch be proc current_char with lexer

    Note: Radix-prefixed integers (0x / 0b / 0o)
    If ch is equal to 48:
        Let next_ch be proc peek_char with lexer, 1
        Let is_radix be 0
        If next_ch is equal to 120:
            Set is_radix to 1
        End If
        If next_ch is equal to 88:
            Set is_radix to 1
        End If
        If next_ch is equal to 98:
            Set is_radix to 1
        End If
        If next_ch is equal to 66:
            Set is_radix to 1
        End If
        If next_ch is equal to 111:
            Set is_radix to 1
        End If
        If next_ch is equal to 79:
            Set is_radix to 1
        End If

        If is_radix is equal to 1:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            While 1 is equal to 1:
                Set ch to proc current_char with lexer
                Let is_hex be proc is_hex_digit with ch
                If is_hex is equal to 1:
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                Otherwise:
                    If ch is equal to 95:
                        proc advance_char with lexer
                    Otherwise:
                        Break
                    End If
                End If
            End While

            Let radix_end be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
            Let radix_lexeme be proc ruby_substring with source, start_pos, radix_end
            Let radix_token be proc create_token with TOKEN_INTEGER, radix_lexeme, line, column
            Return radix_token
        End If
    End If

    Let is_float be 0

    Note: Integer part
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Set ch to proc current_char with lexer
        Let is_dig be proc is_digit with ch
        If is_dig is equal to 1:
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise:
            If ch is equal to 95:
                proc advance_char with lexer
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Note: Fractional part (only if a digit follows the dot)
    Set ch to proc current_char with lexer
    If ch is equal to 46:
        Let after_dot be proc peek_char with lexer, 1
        Let frac_dig be proc is_digit with after_dot
        If frac_dig is equal to 1:
            Set is_float to 1
            proc advance_char with lexer
            While 1 is equal to 1:
                Set ch to proc current_char with lexer
                Let d2 be proc is_digit with ch
                If d2 is equal to 1:
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                Otherwise:
                    If ch is equal to 95:
                        proc advance_char with lexer
                    Otherwise:
                        Break
                    End If
                End If
            End While
        End If
    End If

    Note: Exponent
    Set ch to proc current_char with lexer
    If ch is equal to 101:
        Set is_float to 1
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Set ch to proc current_char with lexer
        If ch is equal to 43:
            proc advance_char with lexer
        End If
        If ch is equal to 45:
            proc advance_char with lexer
        End If
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Set ch to proc current_char with lexer
            Let d3 be proc is_digit with ch
            If d3 is equal to 1:
                proc advance_char with lexer
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End While
    Otherwise:
        If ch is equal to 69:
            Set is_float to 1
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Set ch to proc current_char with lexer
            If ch is equal to 43:
                proc advance_char with lexer
            End If
            If ch is equal to 45:
                proc advance_char with lexer
            End If
            While 1 is equal to 1:
                Set ch to proc current_char with lexer
                Let d4 be proc is_digit with ch
                If d4 is equal to 1:
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                Otherwise:
                    Break
                End If
            End While
        End If
    End If

    Let end_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
    Let lexeme be proc ruby_substring with source, start_pos, end_pos

    Let kind be TOKEN_INTEGER
    If is_float is equal to 1:
        Set kind to TOKEN_FLOAT
    End If

    Let token be proc create_token with kind, lexeme, line, column
    Return token
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: String Lexing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Scans a quoted string literal delimited by quote_char (single quote 0x27,
double quote 0x22, or backtick 0x60). Escape sequences are consumed as a
two-byte unit so an escaped delimiter (\" inside a double-quoted string) does
not terminate the literal. The emitted token type is TOKEN_STRING_INTERP if
a #{...} interpolation was seen in a double-quoted or backtick string (single
quotes do not interpolate), otherwise TOKEN_STRING. The lexeme keeps the
opening and closing delimiters so the parser can recover the exact form.
@End Reasoning
Process called "lex_string" takes lexer as Integer, quote_char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex a '...' / "..." / `...` string literal

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 0
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 16
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 24

    Note: interpolation only happens in double-quote / backtick forms
    Let allows_interp be 0
    If quote_char is equal to 34:
        Set allows_interp to 1
    End If
    If quote_char is equal to 96:
        Set allows_interp to 1
    End If

    proc advance_char with lexer
    Let saw_interp be 0

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let ch be proc current_char with lexer

        If ch is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        If ch is equal to quote_char:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Break
        End If

        If ch is equal to 92:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise:
            If ch is equal to 35:
                Let nxt be proc peek_char with lexer, 1
                If nxt is equal to 123:
                    If allows_interp is equal to 1:
                        Set saw_interp to 1
                    End If
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                    Note: consume balanced #{...} body
                    Let depth be 1
                    While depth is greater than 0:
                        Let ic be proc current_char with lexer
                        If ic is equal to 0:
                            Break
                        End If
                        If ic is equal to 123:
                            Set depth to depth plus 1
                            proc advance_char with lexer
                        Otherwise:
                            If ic is equal to 125:
                                Set depth to depth minus 1
                                proc advance_char with lexer
                            Otherwise:
                                proc advance_char with lexer
                            End If
                        End If
                    End While
                Otherwise:
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                End If
            Otherwise:
                proc advance_char with lexer
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Let end_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
    Let lexeme be proc ruby_substring with source, start_pos, end_pos

    Let kind be TOKEN_STRING
    If saw_interp is equal to 1:
        Set kind to TOKEN_STRING_INTERP
    End If

    Let token be proc create_token with kind, lexeme, line, column
    Return token
End Process

@Reasoning:
Scans a %-literal in word/symbol-array form: %w(...) / %W(...) for string
arrays and %i(...) / %I(...) for symbol arrays. The byte after the type
letter selects the closing delimiter via matching_close. The lexeme keeps
the entire %w(...) text so the parser can split it into elements. Emitted as
TOKEN_STRING (word arrays lower to array-of-string literals downstream).
@End Reasoning
Process called "matching_close" takes open as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Map a %-literal opening delimiter to its closing delimiter

    If open is equal to 40:
        Return 41
    End If
    If open is equal to 91:
        Return 93
    End If
    If open is equal to 123:
        Return 125
    End If
    If open is equal to 60:
        Return 62
    End If
    Return open
End Process

Process called "lex_percent_literal" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex a %w / %W / %i / %I array literal

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 0
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 16
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 24

    Note: consume '%' and the type letter (w/W/i/I)
    proc advance_char with lexer
    proc advance_char with lexer

    Let open be proc current_char with lexer
    Let close be proc matching_close with open
    proc advance_char with lexer

    Let depth be 1
    While depth is greater than 0:
        Let ch be proc current_char with lexer
        If ch is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If
        If ch is equal to 92:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise:
            If ch is equal to open:
                If open is not equal to close:
                    Set depth to depth plus 1
                End If
                proc advance_char with lexer
            Otherwise:
                If ch is equal to close:
                    Set depth to depth minus 1
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                Otherwise:
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Let end_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
    Let lexeme be proc ruby_substring with source, start_pos, end_pos
    Let token be proc create_token with TOKEN_STRING, lexeme, line, column
    Return token
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Symbol Lexing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Scans a Ruby symbol following a ':' that is NOT a '::' scope operator. Three
forms: :"quoted symbol", :ident (possibly with a trailing ? ! =), and
operator symbols (:+, :==, :<=>, :[], :[]=). The caller has already verified
the leading ':' is a symbol introducer (the byte before it is not value-
producing and the byte after is a valid symbol start). The lexeme keeps the
leading ':'.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_operator_symbol_char" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if a byte can appear in an operator-method symbol name

    If ch is equal to 43:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 45:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 42:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 47:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 37:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 60:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 62:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 61:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 33:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 126:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 38:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 124:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 94:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 91:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 93:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "lex_symbol" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex a :symbol literal (bare, quoted, or operator form)

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 0
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 16
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 24

    Note: consume the ':'
    proc advance_char with lexer

    Let ch be proc current_char with lexer

    Note: quoted symbol :"..." or :'...'
    If ch is equal to 34:
        proc advance_char with lexer
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Let q be proc current_char with lexer
            If q is equal to 0:
                Break
            End If
            If q is equal to 34:
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Break
            End If
            If q is equal to 92:
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
            Otherwise:
                proc advance_char with lexer
            End If
        End While
        Let qend be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
        Let qlex be proc ruby_substring with source, start_pos, qend
        Let qtok be proc create_token with TOKEN_SYMBOL, qlex, line, column
        Return qtok
    End If

    Note: identifier-form symbol
    Let alpha be proc is_alpha with ch
    If alpha is equal to 1:
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Let c be proc current_char with lexer
            Let an be proc is_alnum with c
            If an is equal to 1:
                proc advance_char with lexer
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End While
        Note: optional trailing predicate/bang/setter sigil
        Let trail be proc current_char with lexer
        If trail is equal to 63:
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise:
            If trail is equal to 33:
                proc advance_char with lexer
            Otherwise:
                If trail is equal to 61:
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Let iend be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
        Let ilex be proc ruby_substring with source, start_pos, iend
        Let itok be proc create_token with TOKEN_SYMBOL, ilex, line, column
        Return itok
    End If

    Note: operator-method symbol (:+, :==, :[]=, ...)
    Let opc be proc is_operator_symbol_char with ch
    If opc is equal to 1:
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Let oc be proc current_char with lexer
            Let isop be proc is_operator_symbol_char with oc
            If isop is equal to 1:
                proc advance_char with lexer
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End While
        Let oend be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
        Let olex be proc ruby_substring with source, start_pos, oend
        Let otok be proc create_token with TOKEN_SYMBOL, olex, line, column
        Return otok
    End If

    Note: lone ':' that did not introduce a symbol - emit a colon token
    Let cend be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
    Let clex be proc ruby_substring with source, start_pos, cend
    Let ctok be proc create_token with TOKEN_COLON, clex, line, column
    Return ctok
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Variable Lexing (@ivar, @@cvar, $gvar)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Scans an instance variable (@name), class variable (@@name), or global
variable ($name). The sigil byte(s) are consumed first to choose the token
type, then the identifier tail. The lexeme keeps the sigil so the parser and
downstream lowering preserve the distinction. A lone '$' followed by a
special global punctuation byte (e.g. $!, $~, $0) consumes that one byte.
@End Reasoning
Process called "lex_instance_or_class_var" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex @ivar or @@cvar

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 0
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 16
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 24

    proc advance_char with lexer
    Let kind be TOKEN_INSTANCE_VAR
    Let second be proc current_char with lexer
    If second is equal to 64:
        Set kind to TOKEN_CLASS_VAR
        proc advance_char with lexer
    End If

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let ch be proc current_char with lexer
        Let an be proc is_alnum with ch
        If an is equal to 1:
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Let end_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
    Let lexeme be proc ruby_substring with source, start_pos, end_pos
    Let token be proc create_token with kind, lexeme, line, column
    Return token
End Process

Process called "lex_global_var" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex $gvar (named or special)

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 0
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 16
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 24

    proc advance_char with lexer
    Let ch be proc current_char with lexer
    Let alpha be proc is_alpha with ch
    If alpha is equal to 1:
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Let c be proc current_char with lexer
            Let an be proc is_alnum with c
            If an is equal to 1:
                proc advance_char with lexer
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End While
    Otherwise:
        Note: special global like $!, $~, $&, $0 - one byte
        If ch is not equal to 0:
            proc advance_char with lexer
        End If
    End If

    Let end_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
    Let lexeme be proc ruby_substring with source, start_pos, end_pos
    Let token be proc create_token with TOKEN_GLOBAL_VAR, lexeme, line, column
    Return token
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Identifier and Keyword Lexing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Scans an identifier or keyword. Ruby method names may end with '?'
(predicate) or '!' (bang); these trailing sigils are consumed so the name
stays one lexeme. A '=' immediately following an identifier is NOT consumed
here (that is a separate assignment/setter token decided by the parser). The
assembled name is classified against the keyword set; an uppercase-led name
that is not a keyword becomes TOKEN_CONSTANT, otherwise TOKEN_IDENTIFIER.
@End Reasoning
Process called "lex_identifier" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex an identifier, constant, or keyword

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 0
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 16
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 24

    Let first be proc current_char with lexer

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let ch be proc current_char with lexer
        Let an be proc is_alnum with ch
        If an is equal to 1:
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Note: trailing ? or ! makes a method name (e.g. empty?, save!)
    Let tail be proc current_char with lexer
    If tail is equal to 63:
        proc advance_char with lexer
    Otherwise:
        If tail is equal to 33:
            Note: only treat ! as a name tail, not !=, by checking it is not followed by =
            Let after_bang be proc peek_char with lexer, 1
            If after_bang is not equal to 61:
                proc advance_char with lexer
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Let end_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
    Let lexeme be proc ruby_substring with source, start_pos, end_pos

    Let keyword_type be proc match_ruby_keyword with lexeme
    If keyword_type is not equal to 0:
        Let kw_token be proc create_token with keyword_type, lexeme, line, column
        Return kw_token
    End If

    Let kind be TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
    Let up be proc is_upper with first
    If up is equal to 1:
        Set kind to TOKEN_CONSTANT
    End If

    Let token be proc create_token with kind, lexeme, line, column
    Return token
End Process

@Reasoning:
Open-coded keyword recogniser dispatched on the first byte to keep the common
identifier fall-through fast. Covers every Ruby reserved word the parser
distinguishes. Returns the matching TOKEN_* constant, or 0 (no keyword) so
the caller falls back to identifier/constant classification.
@End Reasoning
Process called "match_ruby_keyword" takes text as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Map an identifier spelling to its keyword token, or 0

    Let first_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with text, 0

    Note: 'a' - alias, and
    If first_char is equal to 97:
        Let m be proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "alias"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_ALIAS
        End If
        Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "and"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_AND
        End If
    End If

    Note: 'b' - begin, break, BEGIN
    If first_char is equal to 98:
        Let m be proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "begin"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_BEGIN
        End If
        Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "break"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_BREAK
        End If
    End If

    Note: 'B' - BEGIN
    If first_char is equal to 66:
        Let m be proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "BEGIN"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_BEGIN_UPPER
        End If
    End If

    Note: 'c' - class, case
    If first_char is equal to 99:
        Let m be proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "class"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_CLASS
        End If
        Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "case"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_CASE
        End If
    End If

    Note: 'd' - def, do, defined?
    If first_char is equal to 100:
        Let m be proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "def"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_DEF
        End If
        Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "do"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_DO
        End If
        Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "defined?"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_DEFINED
        End If
    End If

    Note: 'e' - end, elsif, else, ensure, END
    If first_char is equal to 101:
        Let m be proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "end"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_END
        End If
        Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "elsif"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_ELSIF
        End If
        Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "else"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_ELSE
        End If
        Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "ensure"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_ENSURE
        End If
    End If

    Note: 'E' - END
    If first_char is equal to 69:
        Let m be proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "END"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_END_UPPER
        End If
    End If

    Note: 'f' - for, false
    If first_char is equal to 102:
        Let m be proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "for"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_FOR
        End If
        Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "false"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_FALSE
        End If
    End If

    Note: 'i' - if, in
    If first_char is equal to 105:
        Let m be proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "if"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_IF
        End If
        Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "in"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_IN
        End If
    End If

    Note: 'l' - lambda
    If first_char is equal to 108:
        Let m be proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "lambda"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_LAMBDA
        End If
    End If

    Note: 'm' - module
    If first_char is equal to 109:
        Let m be proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "module"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_MODULE
        End If
    End If

    Note: 'n' - nil, next, not
    If first_char is equal to 110:
        Let m be proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "nil"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_NIL
        End If
        Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "next"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_NEXT
        End If
        Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "not"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_NOT
        End If
    End If

    Note: 'o' - or
    If first_char is equal to 111:
        Let m be proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "or"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_OR
        End If
    End If

    Note: 'p' - proc
    If first_char is equal to 112:
        Let m be proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "proc"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_PROC
        End If
    End If

    Note: 'r' - return, rescue, redo, retry
    If first_char is equal to 114:
        Let m be proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "return"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_RETURN
        End If
        Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "rescue"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_RESCUE
        End If
        Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "redo"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_REDO
        End If
        Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "retry"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_RETRY
        End If
    End If

    Note: 's' - self, super
    If first_char is equal to 115:
        Let m be proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "self"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_SELF
        End If
        Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "super"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_SUPER
        End If
    End If

    Note: 't' - then, true
    If first_char is equal to 116:
        Let m be proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "then"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_THEN
        End If
        Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "true"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_TRUE
        End If
    End If

    Note: 'u' - unless, until, undef
    If first_char is equal to 117:
        Let m be proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "unless"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_UNLESS
        End If
        Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "until"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_UNTIL
        End If
        Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "undef"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_UNDEF
        End If
    End If

    Note: 'w' - while, when
    If first_char is equal to 119:
        Let m be proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "while"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_WHILE
        End If
        Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "when"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_WHEN
        End If
    End If

    Note: 'y' - yield
    If first_char is equal to 121:
        Let m be proc string_equals from StringCore with text, "yield"
        If m is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_YIELD
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Regex Lexing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Scans a /.../ regular-expression literal. The caller decides (via the
regex-context heuristic in next_token) that the leading '/' starts a regex
rather than a division operator. Escapes are consumed two bytes at a time so
\/ does not terminate the literal; a character class [...] is tracked so a
'/' inside it is literal. Trailing flag letters (imxounse) are consumed into
the lexeme. Emitted as TOKEN_REGEXP keeping the slashes and flags.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_regex_flag" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if a byte is a Ruby regex flag letter

    If ch is equal to 105:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 109:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 120:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 111:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 117:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 110:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 115:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 101:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "lex_regex" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex a /regex/flags literal

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 0
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 16
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 24

    proc advance_char with lexer
    Let in_class be 0

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let ch be proc current_char with lexer
        If ch is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If
        If ch is equal to 92:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise:
            If ch is equal to 91:
                Set in_class to 1
                proc advance_char with lexer
            Otherwise:
                If ch is equal to 93:
                    Set in_class to 0
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                Otherwise:
                    If ch is equal to 47:
                        If in_class is equal to 0:
                            proc advance_char with lexer
                            Break
                        Otherwise:
                            proc advance_char with lexer
                        End If
                    Otherwise:
                        proc advance_char with lexer
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Note: consume trailing flags
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let f be proc current_char with lexer
        Let isf be proc is_regex_flag with f
        If isf is equal to 1:
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Let end_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
    Let lexeme be proc ruby_substring with source, start_pos, end_pos
    Let token be proc create_token with TOKEN_REGEXP, lexeme, line, column
    Return token
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Main Tokenizer
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Produces the next token. The previous token type is threaded in as prev_type
so the scanner can resolve Ruby's two context-sensitive ambiguities without a
separate parser pass:
  - '/' after a value-producing token (identifier, literal, ')', ']') is
    division; after anything else (start of expression) it opens a regex.
  - A symbol introducer ':' is only a symbol when not preceded by a value and
    when followed by a symbol-start byte; '::' is always the scope operator.
prev_type is 0 at start of file. Horizontal whitespace and comments are
skipped first; a logical newline surfaces as TOKEN_NEWLINE. EOF yields
TOKEN_EOF with a 0 lexeme.
@End Reasoning
Process called "prev_is_value" takes prev_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Whether prev_type closes a value (so '/' divides, ':' is a colon)

    If prev_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
        Return 1
    End If
    If prev_type is equal to TOKEN_CONSTANT:
        Return 1
    End If
    If prev_type is equal to TOKEN_INTEGER:
        Return 1
    End If
    If prev_type is equal to TOKEN_FLOAT:
        Return 1
    End If
    If prev_type is equal to TOKEN_STRING:
        Return 1
    End If
    If prev_type is equal to TOKEN_STRING_INTERP:
        Return 1
    End If
    If prev_type is equal to TOKEN_SYMBOL:
        Return 1
    End If
    If prev_type is equal to TOKEN_INSTANCE_VAR:
        Return 1
    End If
    If prev_type is equal to TOKEN_CLASS_VAR:
        Return 1
    End If
    If prev_type is equal to TOKEN_GLOBAL_VAR:
        Return 1
    End If
    If prev_type is equal to TOKEN_RPAREN:
        Return 1
    End If
    If prev_type is equal to TOKEN_RBRACKET:
        Return 1
    End If
    If prev_type is equal to TOKEN_RBRACE:
        Return 1
    End If
    If prev_type is equal to TOKEN_NIL:
        Return 1
    End If
    If prev_type is equal to TOKEN_TRUE:
        Return 1
    End If
    If prev_type is equal to TOKEN_FALSE:
        Return 1
    End If
    If prev_type is equal to TOKEN_SELF:
        Return 1
    End If
    If prev_type is equal to TOKEN_END:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "next_token" takes lexer as Integer, prev_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Produce the next token; prev_type resolves regex/symbol ambiguity

    Note: Skip horizontal whitespace and comments (including =begin/=end)
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        proc skip_hspace with lexer

        Let ch be proc current_char with lexer

        If ch is equal to 35:
            proc skip_line_comment with lexer
        Otherwise:
            If ch is equal to 61:
                Note: =begin block comment only at logical line start
                Let bc be proc at_block_comment_open with lexer
                If bc is equal to 1:
                    Let col_here be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 24
                    If col_here is equal to 1:
                        proc skip_block_comment with lexer
                    Otherwise:
                        Break
                    End If
                Otherwise:
                    Break
                End If
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 16
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 24
    Let ch be proc current_char with lexer

    Note: EOF
    If ch is equal to 0:
        Let eof_tok be proc create_token with TOKEN_EOF, 0, line, column
        Return eof_tok
    End If

    Note: Newline (statement terminator)
    If ch is equal to 10:
        Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 0
        Let nl_start be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Let nl_end be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
        Let nl_lex be proc ruby_substring with source, nl_start, nl_end
        Let nl_tok be proc create_token with TOKEN_NEWLINE, nl_lex, line, column
        Return nl_tok
    End If

    Note: Numbers
    Let is_dig be proc is_digit with ch
    If is_dig is equal to 1:
        Let num_tok be proc lex_number with lexer
        Return num_tok
    End If

    Note: Instance / class variables (@x, @@x)
    If ch is equal to 64:
        Let iv_tok be proc lex_instance_or_class_var with lexer
        Return iv_tok
    End If

    Note: Global variable ($x)
    If ch is equal to 36:
        Let gv_tok be proc lex_global_var with lexer
        Return gv_tok
    End If

    Note: %w / %W / %i / %I array literals
    If ch is equal to 37:
        Let pn be proc peek_char with lexer, 1
        Let pv be proc prev_is_value with prev_type
        If pv is equal to 0:
            If pn is equal to 119:
                Let pw_tok be proc lex_percent_literal with lexer
                Return pw_tok
            End If
            If pn is equal to 87:
                Let pW_tok be proc lex_percent_literal with lexer
                Return pW_tok
            End If
            If pn is equal to 105:
                Let pi_tok be proc lex_percent_literal with lexer
                Return pi_tok
            End If
            If pn is equal to 73:
                Let pI_tok be proc lex_percent_literal with lexer
                Return pI_tok
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Identifiers and keywords
    Let alpha be proc is_alpha with ch
    If alpha is equal to 1:
        Let id_tok be proc lex_identifier with lexer
        Return id_tok
    End If

    Note: Strings and backtick command literals
    If ch is equal to 34:
        Let s1 be proc lex_string with lexer, 34
        Return s1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 39:
        Let s2 be proc lex_string with lexer, 39
        Return s2
    End If
    If ch is equal to 96:
        Let s3 be proc lex_string with lexer, 96
        Return s3
    End If

    Note: Symbol vs colon vs scope operator
    If ch is equal to 58:
        Let after be proc peek_char with lexer, 1
        If after is equal to 58:
            Note: '::' scope resolution operator
            Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 0
            Let sc_start be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Let sc_end be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
            Let sc_lex be proc ruby_substring with source, sc_start, sc_end
            Let sc_tok be proc create_token with TOKEN_SCOPE, sc_lex, line, column
            Return sc_tok
        End If
        Let pv be proc prev_is_value with prev_type
        Let after_alpha be proc is_alpha with after
        Let after_op be proc is_operator_symbol_char with after
        Let after_quote be 0
        If after is equal to 34:
            Set after_quote to 1
        End If
        Let symbolish be 0
        If after_alpha is equal to 1:
            Set symbolish to 1
        End If
        If after_op is equal to 1:
            Set symbolish to 1
        End If
        If after_quote is equal to 1:
            Set symbolish to 1
        End If
        If symbolish is equal to 1:
            If pv is equal to 0:
                Let sym_tok be proc lex_symbol with lexer
                Return sym_tok
            End If
        End If
        Note: plain colon (hash value separator, ternary else)
        Let source2 be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 0
        Let co_start be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Let co_end be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
        Let co_lex be proc ruby_substring with source2, co_start, co_end
        Let co_tok be proc create_token with TOKEN_COLON, co_lex, line, column
        Return co_tok
    End If

    Note: Regex vs division
    If ch is equal to 47:
        Let pv be proc prev_is_value with prev_type
        If pv is equal to 0:
            Let rx_tok be proc lex_regex with lexer
            Return rx_tok
        End If
    End If

    Note: ---- Multi-character operators ----
    Let next_ch be proc peek_char with lexer, 1
    Let next2 be proc peek_char with lexer, 2
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 0

    Note: Three-character: ... <=> **= <<= >>=
    If ch is equal to 46:
        If next_ch is equal to 46:
            If next2 is equal to 46:
                Let s be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Let e be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
                Let lx be proc ruby_substring with source, s, e
                Let tk be proc create_token with TOKEN_RANGE_EXCL, lx, line, column
                Return tk
            End If
            Let s2 be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Let e2 be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
            Let lx2 be proc ruby_substring with source, s2, e2
            Let tk2 be proc create_token with TOKEN_RANGE_INCL, lx2, line, column
            Return tk2
        End If
    End If

    If ch is equal to 60:
        If next_ch is equal to 61:
            If next2 is equal to 62:
                Let s be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Let e be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
                Let lx be proc ruby_substring with source, s, e
                Let tk be proc create_token with TOKEN_SPACESHIP, lx, line, column
                Return tk
            End If
        End If
        If next_ch is equal to 60:
            If next2 is equal to 61:
                Let s be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Let e be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
                Let lx be proc ruby_substring with source, s, e
                Let tk be proc create_token with TOKEN_LSHIFT_ASSIGN, lx, line, column
                Return tk
            End If
        End If
    End If

    If ch is equal to 62:
        If next_ch is equal to 62:
            If next2 is equal to 61:
                Let s be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Let e be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
                Let lx be proc ruby_substring with source, s, e
                Let tk be proc create_token with TOKEN_RSHIFT_ASSIGN, lx, line, column
                Return tk
            End If
        End If
    End If

    If ch is equal to 42:
        If next_ch is equal to 42:
            If next2 is equal to 61:
                Let s be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Let e be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
                Let lx be proc ruby_substring with source, s, e
                Let tk be proc create_token with TOKEN_POWER_ASSIGN, lx, line, column
                Return tk
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Two-character operators
    Let pair_token be proc lex_two_char_operator with lexer, ch, next_ch, line, column
    If pair_token is not equal to 0:
        Return pair_token
    End If

    Note: Single-character tokens
    Let single_start be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
    proc advance_char with lexer
    Let single_end be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
    Let lexeme be proc ruby_substring with source, single_start, single_end

    Let single_token be proc single_char_token with ch, lexeme, line, column
    Return single_token
End Process

@Reasoning:
Two-character operator recogniser, factored out of next_token to keep that
dispatcher legible. Returns a token when the (ch, next_ch) pair forms a known
two-character operator (consuming both bytes), or 0 to signal the caller to
fall through to single-character handling. The three-character forms (...,
<=>, **=, <<=, >>=) are handled in next_token before this is called, so the
two-char cases here never shadow them.
@End Reasoning
Process called "lex_two_char_operator" takes lexer as Integer, ch as Integer, next_ch as Integer, line as Integer, column as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Recognise a two-character operator pair, or return 0

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 0

    Note: == === =~ =>
    If ch is equal to 61:
        If next_ch is equal to 61:
            Let third be proc peek_char with lexer, 2
            If third is equal to 61:
                Let s be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Let e be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
                Let lx be proc ruby_substring with source, s, e
                Return proc create_token with TOKEN_CASE_EQUAL, lx, line, column
            End If
            Return proc emit_two with lexer, TOKEN_EQUAL_EQUAL, line, column
        End If
        If next_ch is equal to 126:
            Return proc emit_two with lexer, TOKEN_MATCH, line, column
        End If
        If next_ch is equal to 62:
            Return proc emit_two with lexer, TOKEN_HASHROCKET, line, column
        End If
    End If

    Note: != !~
    If ch is equal to 33:
        If next_ch is equal to 61:
            Return proc emit_two with lexer, TOKEN_NOT_EQUAL, line, column
        End If
        If next_ch is equal to 126:
            Return proc emit_two with lexer, TOKEN_NOT_MATCH, line, column
        End If
    End If

    Note: <= << <-style ; < handled single
    If ch is equal to 60:
        If next_ch is equal to 61:
            Return proc emit_two with lexer, TOKEN_LESS_EQUAL, line, column
        End If
        If next_ch is equal to 60:
            Return proc emit_two with lexer, TOKEN_LSHIFT, line, column
        End If
    End If

    Note: >= >>
    If ch is equal to 62:
        If next_ch is equal to 61:
            Return proc emit_two with lexer, TOKEN_GREATER_EQUAL, line, column
        End If
        If next_ch is equal to 62:
            Return proc emit_two with lexer, TOKEN_RSHIFT, line, column
        End If
    End If

    Note: ** *=
    If ch is equal to 42:
        If next_ch is equal to 42:
            Return proc emit_two with lexer, TOKEN_POWER, line, column
        End If
        If next_ch is equal to 61:
            Return proc emit_two with lexer, TOKEN_STAR_ASSIGN, line, column
        End If
    End If

    Note: += -= ->
    If ch is equal to 43:
        If next_ch is equal to 61:
            Return proc emit_two with lexer, TOKEN_PLUS_ASSIGN, line, column
        End If
    End If
    If ch is equal to 45:
        If next_ch is equal to 61:
            Return proc emit_two with lexer, TOKEN_MINUS_ASSIGN, line, column
        End If
        If next_ch is equal to 62:
            Return proc emit_two with lexer, TOKEN_ARROW, line, column
        End If
    End If

    Note: /= %=
    If ch is equal to 47:
        If next_ch is equal to 61:
            Return proc emit_two with lexer, TOKEN_SLASH_ASSIGN, line, column
        End If
    End If
    If ch is equal to 37:
        If next_ch is equal to 61:
            Return proc emit_two with lexer, TOKEN_PERCENT_ASSIGN, line, column
        End If
    End If

    Note: && &&= &. &=
    If ch is equal to 38:
        If next_ch is equal to 38:
            Let third be proc peek_char with lexer, 2
            If third is equal to 61:
                Let s be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Let e be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
                Let lx be proc ruby_substring with source, s, e
                Return proc create_token with TOKEN_AND_ASSIGN, lx, line, column
            End If
            Return proc emit_two with lexer, TOKEN_AND_AND, line, column
        End If
        If next_ch is equal to 46:
            Return proc emit_two with lexer, TOKEN_SAFE_NAV, line, column
        End If
        If next_ch is equal to 61:
            Return proc emit_two with lexer, TOKEN_AMP_ASSIGN, line, column
        End If
    End If

    Note: || ||= |=
    If ch is equal to 124:
        If next_ch is equal to 124:
            Let third be proc peek_char with lexer, 2
            If third is equal to 61:
                Let s be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Let e be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
                Let lx be proc ruby_substring with source, s, e
                Return proc create_token with TOKEN_OR_ASSIGN, lx, line, column
            End If
            Return proc emit_two with lexer, TOKEN_OR_OR, line, column
        End If
        If next_ch is equal to 61:
            Return proc emit_two with lexer, TOKEN_PIPE_ASSIGN, line, column
        End If
    End If

    Note: ^=
    If ch is equal to 94:
        If next_ch is equal to 61:
            Return proc emit_two with lexer, TOKEN_CARET_ASSIGN, line, column
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Consumes exactly two bytes at the cursor and builds a token of the given type
whose lexeme is those two bytes. Shared by every two-character operator case
so the consume/slice pattern lives in one place.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_two" takes lexer as Integer, token_type as Integer, line as Integer, column as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Consume two bytes and emit a token of the given type

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 0
    Let s be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
    proc advance_char with lexer
    proc advance_char with lexer
    Let e be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with lexer, 8
    Let lx be proc ruby_substring with source, s, e
    Return proc create_token with token_type, lx, line, column
End Process

@Reasoning:
Single-character token classifier. Called after the cursor has already
consumed the one byte (so the lexeme is materialised); maps the byte value to
its punctuation/operator token type, or TOKEN_ERROR for an unrecognised byte
so the parser can report it precisely.
@End Reasoning
Process called "single_char_token" takes ch as Integer, lexeme as Integer, line as Integer, column as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Map a single consumed byte to its token

    If ch is equal to 40:
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LPAREN, lexeme, line, column
    End If
    If ch is equal to 41:
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_RPAREN, lexeme, line, column
    End If
    If ch is equal to 123:
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LBRACE, lexeme, line, column
    End If
    If ch is equal to 125:
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_RBRACE, lexeme, line, column
    End If
    If ch is equal to 91:
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LBRACKET, lexeme, line, column
    End If
    If ch is equal to 93:
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_RBRACKET, lexeme, line, column
    End If
    If ch is equal to 44:
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_COMMA, lexeme, line, column
    End If
    If ch is equal to 46:
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_DOT, lexeme, line, column
    End If
    If ch is equal to 59:
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_SEMICOLON, lexeme, line, column
    End If
    If ch is equal to 63:
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_QUESTION, lexeme, line, column
    End If
    If ch is equal to 43:
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_PLUS, lexeme, line, column
    End If
    If ch is equal to 45:
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_MINUS, lexeme, line, column
    End If
    If ch is equal to 42:
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_STAR, lexeme, line, column
    End If
    If ch is equal to 47:
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_SLASH, lexeme, line, column
    End If
    If ch is equal to 37:
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_PERCENT, lexeme, line, column
    End If
    If ch is equal to 61:
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_ASSIGN, lexeme, line, column
    End If
    If ch is equal to 33:
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_BANG, lexeme, line, column
    End If
    If ch is equal to 60:
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LESS_THAN, lexeme, line, column
    End If
    If ch is equal to 62:
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_GREATER_THAN, lexeme, line, column
    End If
    If ch is equal to 38:
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_AMP, lexeme, line, column
    End If
    If ch is equal to 124:
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_PIPE, lexeme, line, column
    End If
    If ch is equal to 94:
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_CARET, lexeme, line, column
    End If
    If ch is equal to 126:
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_TILDE, lexeme, line, column
    End If

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_ERROR, lexeme, line, column
End Process

